3) Reed St. Claire the rich truant. Has a white Toyota Tacoma TRD Sport with pink underglow and a "Salt Life" sticker. His parents are old timber money, he flunked out of UW, and they forced him to attend Peninsula College to "learn a real trade" as humiliation. He wants to flee to Bali or Tokyo. Looks similar enough to Syl. "Attend my classes, sit my exams, live in my dorm. My family pays the bills; you get a warm bed and a transcript. Just don't get caught."

4) Eileen Marsh the old lady with binoculars, a snoopy agressive neighbor.

10 Key NPCs:

1) Casey the trespasser: "the ground". Blogger, cryptid hunter. Known as Sam "Squatch" Bellevue online? Or just Casey? Her blog focuses on you until you befriend her, passively increasing heat. Interacting with her also teaches you about abandoned buildings and dark alleys for quick escapes when possessed. Meet her by entering any dark alley/abandoned building. Befirend her by doing a fetch quest? Psychological theme is feeling at home in the city, establishing basic sense of security. Week 1

2) Solomon Vance: "the structure". Peninsula College retention specialist for Building Trades & Applied Sciences. Gets hired on week 3 by the new hardass dean. Reed's parents also call asking to assign someone, mentioning the dropout history. Meet Mr. Vance by attending college starting week 3 (the first progress-report deadline). Solomon is assigned to “Reed St. Clair” on Monday of Week 3. He approaches you before class with a mandatory one-on-one success coaching session after classes same day. He is anxious, self-interested, and compromised. He is embezzling lab copper and selling it to a scrap dealer because his wife has medical debt. Befriend Mr. Vance by helping him cover up an accident while also attending everything for 2 weeks. Or by blackmailing him. If you don't do either you'll have to keep attending every day and he won't cover up for you, and if you skip too much you'll get assigned a buddy who follows you at school (or check out spots + times). Reward for befriending is also unlocking a set of Social Engineering Protocols that you'd otherwise have to find through other secret actions around town. These are all related to the campus, but some are universal. That means some later key character can still teach you more social engineering protocols. Killing Mr. Vance is not meta even in violent route, because it would most likely get you kicked out or something similar, but maybe there should be something for the players who want a hardcore experience, so when you kill him you get some big challenge? The psychological theme is about establishing control over your schedule, not just living in panic mode but trusting in tomorrow. Week 3

3) Danny Kowalski: "the drive". Polish-American, 34, small town crook, runs Danny’s Auto Salvage on the east industrial strip near Highway 101. Wears a navy Dickies coverall with the name patch torn off, a flat cap soaked in axle grease. Drives a 1996 Ford F-250 OBS, lifted, rusted through the bed, runs like a tank. Meet him at his shop, your only way to get a car, easy part-time jobs, or crafting materials. Kowalski has a corporate rival - Harbor Auto Solutions (HAS), a Bellingham-based chain planning to rezone the junkyard. They are building a “Certified Pre-Owned Supercenter” with 24-hour security, credit-check kiosks, and a service center that reports all VINs to the state DMV in real time. Befriend Kowalski by doing small jobs for him to help business stay relevant enough against HAS, or ignore or sabotage him to make the chop shop disappear. Kill him and get an option to take over his shop yourself. Psychological theme is about growing past surviving, getting back up against all odds and thriving. Week 5

4) Tessa “Tess” Braddock : "Ego and Shadow". By now Syl feels angry and strong enough to want to conquer the curse rather than keep running away. Tess is 31, former Coast Guard rescue swimmer, medically discharged after a night operation in the Strait of Juan de Fuca where she was submerged for fourteen minutes in 38-degree water. She survived. She wears a faded orange drysuit cut into a jacket, has a scar across her left temple from the rescue boat’s propeller, and speaks in short sentences because her hypoxia damaged her verbal processing. Tessa’s gym is on the waterfront industrial strip — the exact corridor you use to move between Danny’s yard, the smuggling dock, and the 101 on-ramp. She goes outside at 5:00 AM every morning, hauling the cold plunge tub onto the dock, dumping in Strait water, and sitting in it for exactly six minutes. She has breakfast every morning at the Coast Guard station cafeteria with her former colleagues, where she gossips. Meet her in any of those spots. First time you approach her, your possession countdown breaks and starts moving up and down rapidly, and you nearly attack her but she doesn't flinch and just dodges precisely. (not sure why in lore yet). She decides you have the same condition as her, but is suspicious. Ignoring Tessa leads to icreased difficulties with dumping evidence off Ediz Hook or using the smuggling dock? This is the first mention of this, why is this a threat? Maybe the curse mechanics change dramatically on week 7, forcing you to seek out ways to gain more control over it and Tessa is somehow connected to it? The Current meditations are unlocked as new gameplay to slowly level up your control of the curse the more you practice. Consistency is more important than volume but there should be rewards for both. Your control scales with the current zone level too, so you want to try to get +5 or -5 in all zones one by one to achieve max control, either to use it to disable possessions or to make them more powerful. At this stage playstyle in peaceful/violet routes finally diverge completely as the violent route gives you a way to become powerful enough to grow into a one man army to fight off police, reign terror on civillians, while establishing your chop shop as your base. You're only starting out though. Befriend Tessa by becoming her training partner? Complete a series of meditations where you fight side by side with her against phantoms? Spar against each other like martial arts? Kill her and get a special hardcore version of the Current, maybe a way to train shadows like your goons and then bring them into the real world to fight armed lawmen with bare hands or crafted weapons. Not sure why that would happen when you kill her specifically though. The psychological theme is about taking control of your weaknesses. Week 7

5) Jesse "J.D." Drummond : "the trace". Opens elk hunting season (Muzzleloader Early: Oct. 3 – 9 Modern Firearm: Oct. 31 – Nov. 18) You unlock fishing, foraging and hunting, and can get a license to do that as well as buy a gun/rifle/muzzleloader. However the woods become filled with hunters who immediately open fire if you get possessed while in the woods, making fishing and hunting troublesome. The problems with this idea are that there's no hunger need, no reason to fish/hunt/forage or ever visit the forest really. Maybe we could add a cooking feature where different meals give you different buffs or maybe on week 9 a shop opens where you can sell goods from the forest. Maybe more magic lore can be introduced - there are mutated mycelia in the lore that can power up your curse, but maybe that's unnecessary to add. Maybe cryptids should be added as real entities you can find? Maybe animals can attack you in the woods? Anyway, you can meet Jessy by entering the woods starting week 9. Befriend him by hunting together? Kill him to get on the best mid-late game rifles. Ignore him and idk maybe he hunts you? honestly no idea why a random hunter would be a threat. The psychological theme is probably something about guns. murica. freedom. idk. Week 9

